comments.body:
That makes sense.
> it doesn't matter if we do another syscall, as no one measures the performance of errors cases

> Furthermore, using stat adds another point where Podman can fail. In that case, the error would mostly be similar to what the labeling function would provide.

I agree with you.

Then how about adding these codes, in [this line](https://github.com/containers/podman/blob/ac2d567910b61b8ebb8b2490ca33a3ba86884de5/libpod/container_internal_common.go#L3159)?

```golang
....
	err := label.Relabel(src, mountLabel, shared)
	if errors.Is(err, unix.ENOTSUP) {
		logrus.Debugf("Labeling not supported on %q", src)
		return nil
	}
	if errors.Is(err, unix.EPERM){
		currentUID := uint32(os.Getuid())
		return fmt.Errorf("Labeling failed: likely due to a file owned by another user (current user: uid %d): %w", currentUID, err)
	}
	return err
}
```
If this looks good to you, I will also add some tests [here](https://github.com/containers/podman/blob/90a03ca080d42ccb0c9c3051f42d8ba828686b6c/test/e2e/run_selinux_test.go#L315), if possible

I have submitted a PR #28155 to address this. It catches the unix.EPERM error during relabeling and wraps it in a more descriptive message that identifies the problematic path and the current user's UID, as discussed.

I have manually verified the fix on Fedora 43 by reproducing the root-owned file scenario in a rootless container.

@Honny1, what do you think?
